	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>'South Africanisation' is supported by new policies</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The South African government launched a series of consultations with fishing communities in November 2004 to discuss draft policies for each of its fisheries. Of particular interest is the very successful hake-fishery sector, comprising 130 vessels that employ about 700 crew, with earnings in excess of R1 million per vessel every year - thanks especially to the increased European demand for hake.</p><p> In early December 2004, the South African government allocated commercial fishing rights for tuna longlining and swordfish longlining to local fishermen for the first time. This has met an important objective of South African fisheries policy: 'the South Africanisation of the fishery'. Historically, South Africa's valuable longline tuna and swordfish stocks have been exploited by foreign coastal states. All the rights recently allocated were to South African-owned entities.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2282" target="_self">Globefish hake market report, October 2004</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.nnp.co.za/AFR/HTML/MediaDetail.asp?MEDIAID=2554&amp;ID=0" target="_self">NNP press release, November 29th 2004</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.afrol.com/articles/14937" target="_self">Afrol news, December 7th 2004</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> A common developmental objective for many ACP countries' fisheries sectors is to increase the benefit flows from national fisheries exploitation to coastal communities. But with fish stocks becoming increasingly depleted, achieving this objective is far from easy. A case in point is the deep-sea hake fishery of South Africa. In this case, the South African government grants almost three-quarters of the quota for deep sea hake to a very few established operators like Irving and Johnston (I and J) and Sea Harvest. The government has also promised not to reduce the fishing quotas allocated to these companies for three years, giving them a clear advantage over the emerging 'empowerment' companies formed by previously disadvantaged groups. It comes as no surprise that the empowerment companies are objecting to these quota privileges, which encourage inequality. But given that hake fishing is South Africa's most lucrative export-oriented fishery activity, the government faces the dilemma of increasing equity in the fishery on the one hand, or controlling new entrants on the other so as to protect investment and existing jobs.</p><p> The implementation of a new 'consultative' fisheries policy for hake should improve the possibilities for coastal communities and previously disadvantaged groups to benefit from this fishery. South Africa, along with Namibia and Argentina, is one of the top hake suppliers on the EU market. Moves towards the 'democratisation' of the hake fishery should be supported, for example through such trade-related measures as preferential market access. However, up to now South Africa has been unable to gain such preferential access because of the conditionality clause in the Trade, Development and Cooperation Agreement (TDCA) signed in 1999, that makes such access conditional on the signing of a fisheries agreement with the EU.</p><p> In the case of the tuna fishery, it is worth noting that South Africa, along with Namibia, is one of the few ACP countries that has successfully 'nationalised' fisheries resources previously exploited by foreign vessels (from Europe and east Asia). One of the key factors in this success has been the significant investment in fisheries management, at both national and regional level (for example through monitoring, control and surveillance programmes). Such investment is particularly important for fisheries that are exploited far off-shore, as in the case of tuna.</p><p> These are lessons that could be learned by other ACP countries, like Angola and Cape Verde, which lack adequate means to sustain the management and regulation of such fisheries. A process of nationalising tuna fisheries exploitation without adequate capacity for management and control is unlikely to result in sustainable benefits accruing to the country concerned.</p><p> Efforts to improve fisheries management, particularly at regional level, should be supported by the EU, through both market-related measures (preferential access) and through the financing of specially designated management and control programmes.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
